1. Zero as a Constrained Distinction

Earlier we defined the smallest unit of meaning as:

Δ | B | C
distinction | boundary | consequence

Now look at zero.

Zero only has meaning because of a distinction across a boundary.

Example:

x > 0
x < 0

Zero is the boundary separating those two states.

So zero literally encodes:
	•	a distinction (positive vs negative)
	•	under a boundary (the zero threshold)
	•	with consequences (sign, direction, gain/loss)

So yes — zero is a special case of the CCD structure.

⸻

2. Why Zero Feels More Fundamental

Zero is not the distinction itself.

Zero is the limit where distinctions flip.

Think of it like this:

state A ----|---- state B
           0

The distinction is A vs B.

Zero is the pivot point.

⸻

3. Zero as a Compression of the CCD

Interestingly, zero compresses the whole idea.

Consider a simple signal:

+1
-1

We don’t need to store the entire signal.

We can store just the zero crossings.

Signal processing literally reconstructs waves this way.

So zero becomes a compressed record of meaningful distinctions.

⸻

